  "prompt": "Can you be allergic to meat and fish?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible to be allergic to meat and fish, although such allergies are relatively uncommon compared to other food allergies like those to nuts, shellfish, or dairy.\n\n1. **Meat Allergy**:\n   - **Alpha-Gal Syndrome**: One specific type of meat allergy is known as **alpha-gal syndrome**, which is triggered by the carbohydrate molecule **alpha-gal** found in red meat (e.g., beef, pork, lamb). This allergy is often associated with tick bites (e.g., the Lone Star tick in the U.S.) and can cause delayed allergic reactions, sometimes several hours after consuming meat.\n   - Symptoms include hives, swelling, digestive issues, and in severe cases, anaphylaxis.\n\n2. **Fish Allergy**:\n   - Fish allergy is more common than meat allergy and is typically triggered by proteins found in fish like salmon, tuna, or cod. It is distinct from shellfish allergy, which involves crustaceans (e.g., shrimp, crab) and mollusks (e.g., clams, oysters).\n   - Symptoms can include hives, itching, swelling, gastrointestinal distress, and in severe cases, anaphylaxis.\n\n3. **Cross-Reactivity**:\n   - Some individuals allergic to one type of fish may react to other types due to similar proteins, but this isn't always the case.\n   - Meat allergies (e.g., alpha-gal syndrome) are less likely to cross-react with fish, as the allergens are different.\n\nIf you suspect an allergy to meat or fish, consult an allergist for proper diagnosis and management. Allergy testing (e.g., skin prick tests, blood tests) can confirm the allergy, and avoidance of the allergen is the primary treatment. In cases of severe allergies, carrying an epinephrine auto-injector (e.g., EpiPen) is often recommended.",
